                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311020-182-off968 t18311020-182-crimeloc970"></join>. The prisoner had been a <rs id="t18311020-182-deflabel971" type="occupation">shopman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311020-182-defend1242 t18311020-182-deflabel971"></join> of mine, but left me about two months - he came on the 5th of October, to ask if I would give him a character; I said he had better refer to the person he lived with last, but I would go and speak to his mother - I went to wash myself, and while I was doing so he left, saying he would call again; I came into the shop again, and missed my watch, which had hung there.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311020-182-person1245">
                  JOHN 
                  THOMAS PRATLEY
               <interp inst="t18311020-182-person1245" type="surname" value="THOMAS PRATLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311020-182-person1245" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311020-182-person1245" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-officer. I was on duty at Knightsbridge. on the 5th of October, at half-past ten o'clock at night; I saw the prisoner - he walked backwards and forwards till about twenty minutes before twelve; I then asked him if he wanted any one - he said he was waiting for the coffee-shop to open; that he had been to the play, and came out at half-past eleven - I<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183110200071"></xptr>asked what he had about him; he said nothing - I searched him, and found this watch.</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a petition, expressing his contrition for the offence.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 13.</p>
               <p>Recommended to Mercy by the Prosecutor and Jury.</p>
